  "doc_id": "48147",
  "text": "Molecular pathogenesis FCMD, like other dystroglycanopathies (Table 1) , shares an abnormally glycosylated a-dystroglycan protein. FUKUTIN encodes a putative glycosyltransferase based on primary sequence analysis. The muscles of FCMD patients show reduced expression of glycosylated a-dystroglycan [CITATION_1] , although expression of a-dystroglycan polypeptide is present, along with b-dystroglycan, in the sarcolemmal membrane. Loss of glycosylation impairs binding of laminin a2 to a-dystroglycan. Consequently there may be secondary reduction in laminin a2 and basal lamina disruption [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . This finding is a central theme common to all variants in this group of CMD. With regard to central nervous system findings, abnormal neuronal migration can be induced by brain-specific disruption of a-dystroglycan in mice, implicating aberrant glycosylation of dystroglycan in lissencephaly type II [CITATION_6] .",
